  "author_association": "MEMBER",
  "body": "#1797 and #1807 separate user and developer documentation.\n\nHowever, there are a bunch of places where we have \"design documentation\" mixed in with user or developer documentation.   That should probably be separated.   The audiences are quite different.\n## What goes where\n#### User docs\n- description of current concepts and features\n- description of planned features (brief descriptions, with links to design docs for more detail)\n- how concepts fit use cases.\n- use cases for current features (should work)\n- few justifications and little or no discussion of alternatives\n#### Design docs\n- longer descriptions of planned features\n- use cases for planned features (may not work)\n- alternative designs, design tradeoffs, and justifications\n## Specific improvements\n- move docs/access.md to docs/design/access.md.  Link(s) to it from roadmap.md.\n- move docs/identifiers.md to docs/design/identifiers.md.  Put a considerably briefer summary in docs/identifiers.md or inline to elsewhere in user docs.\n- docs/labels.md -- second half of doc is largely design doc.  First half is mostly user docs, but needs concrete runnable examples.\n- docs/namespaces.md should move to docs/design/namespaces.md and there should be a much shorted user doc on namespaces, with some concrete examples.\n- docs/networking.md needs to be split up into user and design parts.\n- docs/pods.md has \"alternatives considered\".  That belongs in design doc.\n- docs/security.md goes to design subdir.  There should be a user documentation that specifically addresses security features in the current system, and that summarizes what we plan to add, with links to design docs.\n",
